      "body" : "@KorayTugay A <code>char</code> is <b>not</b> a code point.  <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/datatypes.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">A <code>char</code> is 16 bits</a> (it&#39;s basically an unsigned <code>short</code>), so it always takes 2 bytes in memory.  An <code>int</code> is needed to represent a 4-byte code point, which is why methods like <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#codePointAt-int-\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">String.codePointAt()</a> return <code>int</code> and not <code>char</code>."
